                            <h1>Ryan Daly
                                13 years old</h1>
                            <audio src="/audio/en/Ryan-Daly.mp3" controls>
                                Recording of Ryan Daly Story
                            </audio>
                            <p>The neighborhood of Chinatown means a lot to my family and I. My whole life revolves around Chinatown in a sense. My elementary school, St. Therese Chinese Catholic School, is in Chinatown, along with my Po Po’s (grandma) house. Every day after school, I go to my Po Po’s house to visit. Po Po cooks a meal for me every day after school so I am not hungry. I do my homework and study there before I leave for the extracurricular activity I have planned for that day.</p>

                            <p>My grandparents come from Hong Kong. My great-grandfather and grandfather came here firstly, and once they settled and saved enough money, they were able to send for my Po Po and Uncle Bill. Before Po Po arrived in Chicago, she learned English for two years in preparation for her move to America. When she came over to the United States, a girl that worked for her helped her to improve her English. Po Po told me that when she came to Chicago, there were no highways other than Lake Shore Drive, but there were more railroad tracks, and there were not ANY restaurants, grocery stores, or bakeries. Many of the future streets were empty prairieland, and the houses that are here now didn’t exist. The boundaries of Chinatown at the time were Cermak Rd. to the north, 23rd St. to the south, Wentworth Ave. to the east, and Princeton Ave. to the west.</p>

                            <p>My mother, her three sisters and brother grew up in Chinatown as well. The boundaries of Chinatown were then Cermak Rd. to the north, 24th Place to the south, Wentworth Ave. to the east, and Princeton Ave. to the west. My mom said that when she was a child, the population of Chinatown was mostly of Italian and Irish descent, and there was a very small Chinese population. Over the years, more Chinese people had started to move in. My aunts remember their favorite candy store, Joe Store, that all of the kids went to buy candy, hang out, and have fun with their friends. As my aunt remembers, there was one grocery store on Wentworth Ave.: Sun Cheong Loong. Sun Cheong Loong had roasted ducks and pork, vegetables, and gifts to buy. Aunt Joann remembers the huge siu mai and fried egg puffs served at Golden Gate, coffee (they added egg shells to their coffee grounds before brewing the coffee), buttered toast, and fried eggs at Kee Kee Cafe, and the enormous cupcakes at Dong Kee. Po Po says the cupcakes were tiny, but huge to my aunt because she was so tiny.</p>

                            <p>I have seen a lot of things changed over the years in the Chinatown neighborhood. The boundaries of Chinatown are now 16th St. to the north, 24th Place to the south, Wentworth Ave. to the east, and Princeton Ave. to the west. There have always been a lot of restaurants, but the the type of food served has changed. Recently, there have been more styles of Chinese cuisine coming into Chinatown (Szechuan, Hunan), and the Cantonese restaurants have closed. There have also been a lot more noodle shops, hot pot restaurants, and different Asian cuisine (Korean, Japanese) that have opened. There was even a Kentucky Fried Chicken in Chinatown Square but it is closed now. Who would want Kentucky Fried Chicken, if I could get roast pork and dumplings! I remember walking around Chinatown, shopping with my grandma, staring at the roasted duck and pork. I remember the live animals, like fish, frogs, crabs, shrimp, and lobsters. My grandma would always buy me a bao from one of the many bakeries. I begged to go into every gift shop, knowing I would find the same toys, but still wanting see if anything had changed. The size of Chinatown has increased greatly since my grandma first came over to the United States.</p>

                            <p>My family has a lot of history in Chinatown, and we have lived in the community for three generations now. We have become attached to the community and the people of Chinatown, and we have no plans of ever leaving this great neighborhood!</p>
